Scenario: Review the following implementation intended to reset a form's UI state when switching view modes.

function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const [name, setName] = useState("");

  return (
    <input
      value={name}
      onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
    />
  );
}

function ProfileEditor({ userId, isViewMode }) {
  return (
    <>
      {isViewMode ? (
        <UserProfile key="view" userId={userId} />
      ) : (
        <UserProfile key="edit" userId={userId} />
      )}
    </>
  );
}

Question:

What will happen to the state inside UserProfile when isViewMode toggles from true to false, and why?
When isViewMode changes, React sees different keys ("view" vs "edit").

Because the keys are different:

React treats them as entirely different component instances
The old component is unmounted
A new component is mounted

As a result, all local state inside UserProfile (such as name) is reset.

This happens because keys are part of component identity in React’s reconciliation algorithm. Changing the key forces React to discard the previous Fiber and create a new one.

